p); err != nil {\\n          return 0, fmt.Errorf(\\\"writing to limited buffer: %w\\\", err)\\n      }\\n      return originalLen, nil\\n  }\\n  ```\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go:97-98] `ReadTranscript` uses `context.Background()` with no timeout.** Most other methods that take no context also use `context.Background()`, but `ReadTranscript` reads potentially large transcript files from an external binary. The `run` method applies `defaultRunTimeout` (30s) when no deadline is set, so this is partially mitigated. However, consider whether 30 seconds is appropriate for large transcripts, or whether callers should be able to pass a context.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go:123-137] `GetSessionID` silently returns empty string on all errors.** While this matches the built-in agent pattern (returning `\\\"\\\"` for no session), swallowing errors from JSON unmarshal or binary execution makes debugging difficult. Consider logging the error at debug level, or at minimum documenting that errors are intentionally swallowed.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go:151-162] `ResolveSessionFile` and `FormatResumeCommand` also silently swallow errors.** Same concern as `GetSessionID`. These methods return empty strings on any failure with no logging. External binary failures (timeouts, crashes) will be invisible to operators.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go:211-212] `ParseHookEvent` reads up to 10MB from stdin but the `maxParseHookBytes` constant is defined locally.** Consider sharing this constant with the `maxOutputBytes` constant (line 428) or at least documenting the relationship. Both are 10MB but serve different purposes (input vs output limits).\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go:33-48] Fallback `RunE` on `hooksCmd` accepts arbitrary args for external agent dispatch but has no validation of the hook name.** The `hookName` (args[1]) is passed directly to `executeAgentHook` without any sanitization or validation. While there is no command injection risk (it goes through JSON protocol), a typo or malformed hook name will produce a confusing error from the external binary's stderr. Consider validating against the agent's declared `HookNames()` after discovery.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go:73] `New(ctx, binPath)` uses the discovery context (5s timeout from hooks_cmd.go).** If there are many external agents on PATH, the 5-second timeout is shared across all of them. Each `New()` call invokes the binary's `info` subcommand. With, say, 10 slow external agents, later ones may time out. Consider using a per-binary timeout instead of a shared context.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external_test.go] No test for `limitedWriter`.** Adding a unit test for `limitedWriter` (including the overflow/truncation case) would catch the bug above and prevent regressions.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go:131-145] `eventJSON` uses `int` for `Type` field.** The Event type constants are defined as `agent.EventType` (likely an int alias). While this works, it couples the external protocol to the internal constant values. If those values ever change, all external agents break silently. Consider documenting the type-to-int mapping in the protocol doc or using string enum values for the protocol layer.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/capabilities.go] The 7 `As*` functions follow an identical pattern.** Consider a generic helper to reduce the boilerplate, e.g., `asCapability[T](ag Agent, check func(DeclaredCaps) bool) (T, bool)`. This would reduce the 7 nearly-identical functions to one-liners. However, this is purely a code style preference and the current approach is explicit and clear.\\n\\n- **[cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go:40-43] PATH scanning reads all directory entries.** For systems with very large PATH directories (e.g., `/usr/bin` with thousands of entries), this iterates every entry looking for the `entire-agent-` prefix. This is unlikely to be a practical performance issue, but worth noting.\\n\\n- **[docs/architecture/external-agent-protocol.md] The Event type values (1-7) are documented but should note they must match Go constants exactly.** If someone implements an external agent from just the docs, they need to know these are authoritative values, not examples.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Excellent protocol documentation.** The `external-agent-protocol.md` file is thorough, with clear examples for every subcommand, shared object definitions, and capability gating explanation. This is the kind of documentation that makes third-party integration feasible.\\n\\n- **Clean capability gating pattern.** The `CapabilityDeclarer` / `As*` helper pattern is well-designed. It preserves backward compatibility with built-in agents (type assertion falls through) while adding explicit capability declaration for external agents. The `wrappedAgent` approach avoids the complexity of dynamic interface composition.\\n\\n- **Thorough test coverage for the `Wrap` function.** Tests cover all combinations: hooks-only, analyzer-only, preparer-only, multiple capabilities, and no capabilities. Each test verifies both positive and negative cases (capability declared true vs false).\\n\\n- **Feature flag gating.** Requiring `external_agents: true` in settings before discovery runs is a sensible default-off approach for a new feature. The settings merge logic and tests are complete.\\n\\n- **Defensive binary execution.** The `run` method applies default timeouts, limits output size, sets `WaitDelay` to prevent goroutine leaks, and passes environment variables cleanly. The `exec.CommandContext` usage with separate args prevents shell injection.\\n\\n- **Good refactoring of `executeAgentHook`.** Extracting the shared logic from `newAgentHookVerbCmdWithLogging` into `executeAgentHook` enables reuse by the external agent fallback path while keeping the logging initialization concern properly separated.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n- **Key concern:** The `limitedWriter.Write` bug (Critical) will cause `cmd.Run()` to fail with `ErrShortWrite` when an external binary produces output exceeding the 10MB limit, rather than silently discarding the excess. This is a correctness issue that could cause hook failures in production with verbose external agents.\\n- **Secondary concerns:** Silent error swallowing in several methods will make debugging external agent issues difficult. The shared 5-second discovery timeout may be insufficient when multiple external agents are present.\\n- **Estimated effort:** ~1 hour. The `limitedWriter` fix is a one-line change. Adding a unit test and improving error logging in the silent-swallow methods is straightforward.\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":274,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":80450,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":274},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYjmmortd8KwDPEnH3dQZ\",\"uuid\":\"1d0a223a-5ad8-4b28-b219-427dc14725bf\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"ac6eec0fc6ad11a59\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_014Zbzs22xZkbfXSZGaZbL3Y\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_016QE3mshzXCTyew8EMnepyc\",\"uuid\":\"e4d37def-1f64-4583-be67-bcc8bf7f9216\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T10:27:07.690Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"e4d37def-1f64-4583-be67-bcc8bf7f9216\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"03df2882-a2af-44d2-ad9e-d4dee3f44781\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"nodo/external-plugins\",\"slug\":\"kind-finding-toast\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"c